[2]
Date: Sat 22 Jan 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Voice of Vietnam, Sat 22 Jan 2005 [edited]
<http://www.vov.org.vn/2005_01_22/english/xahoi1.htm#PM%20orders%20strong%20actions%20to%20stop%20spread%20of%20bird%20flu>

Prime Minister Orders Urgent Action to Prevent Further Spread of Avian
Influenza
--------------------------------------------------
According to the Ministry of Health, 8 people have so far tested
H5N1-positive. Of them, 6 have died, one is in critical condition at the
Tropical Diseases Hospital in Ho Chi Minh City, and the other is being
treated at the Tropical Diseases Hospital in Hanoi.
By Sat 22 Jan 2005, the Tropical Diseases Hospital in Hanoi has received 5
patients with pneumonia, 2 of whom have died. One has been confirmed to
have contracted the H5N1 virus and the other has no test results. Among the
3 remaining patients, one tested positive for H5N1. He is the younger
brother of the dead patient.
Meanwhile, 2 more patients were hospitalised at the Tropical Diseases
Hospital in Ho Chi Minh City on Fri 21 Jan 2995. One of them, coming from
Dong Thap province, died several hours after being hospitalised. Doctors
took blood samples for tests. 6 other children suspected of avian
infections are being treated at Nhi Dong 1 (Children 1) hospital in the city.
The Ministry sent a report on developments of the disease to the Government
and asked for VND80 billion [USD 5 million] to purchase medical equipment,
respirators, and chemicals for the 3 regions across the country. Earlier,
on Thu 20 Jan 2005, Deputy Prime Minister Pham Gia Khiem, on behalf of the
Prime Minister, ordered ministries, ministerial-level agencies, government
agencies and provincial and municipal People's Committees to take strict
measures to prevent the spread of pneumonia caused by avian influenza type
A (H5N1) virus. According to the Health Ministry, pneumonia caused by the
H5N1 avian virus has been developing and becoming complicated. To take
urgent prevention measures, the Government assigned the Health Ministry to
co-operate with other ministries, services and localities to immediately
discover how the H5N1-infected patients contracted the disease; and
urgently to work out a plan to mobilise all existing resources, workforces
and equipment to treat patients when an epidemic occurs, and submit it to
the PM before 27 Jan 2005.
The prevention of avian influenza and its transmission to humans must be
given top priority, Deputy Prime Minister Nguyen Tan Dzung told an
inter-provincial meeting in Hanoi on Fri 21 Jan 2005. He asked localities
and the mass media to boost information dissemination to raise public
awareness about avian influenza. He requested both unaffected and affected
areas to tighten control over poultry slaughtering, processing, and
transportation to prevent the epidemic from spreading.
